opologicalSpace\">TopologicalSpace</a> <span class=\"fn\">N</span></span>]</span></span>\n</span><span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">(<span class=\"fn\">v</span> : <span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"./Mathlib/MeasureTheory/VectorMeasure/Basic.html#MeasureTheory.VectorMeasure\">VectorMeasure</a> <span class=\"fn\">α</span> <span class=\"fn\">M</span></span>)</span></span>\n<span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">(<span class=\"fn\">w</span> : <span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"./Mathlib/MeasureTheory/VectorMeasure/Basic.html#MeasureTheory.VectorMeasure\">VectorMeasure</a> <span class=\"fn\">α</span> <span class=\"fn\">N</span></span>)</span></span>\n<span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./foundational_types.html\">Prop</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"Two vector measures `v` and `w` are said to be mutually singular if there exists a measurable\nset `s`, such that for all `t ⊆ s`, `v t = 0` and for all `t ⊆ sᶜ`, `w t = 0`.\n\nWe note that we do not require the measurability of `t` in the definition since this makes it easier\nto use. This is equivalent to the definition which requires measurability. To prove\n`MutuallySingular` with the measurability condition, use\n`MeasureTheory.VectorMeasure.MutuallySingular.mk`. ","docLink":"./Mathlib/MeasureTheory/VectorMeasure/Basic.html#MeasureTheory.VectorMeasure.MutuallySingular","kind":"def","line":1093,"name":"MeasureTheory.VectorMeasure.MutuallySingular","sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/0f1dd7505c3d08b5feb82300ccc73179a457bf51/Mathlib/MeasureTheory/VectorMeasure/Basic.lean#L1093-L1101"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">theorem</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./Mathlib/MeasureTheory/VectorMeasure/Basic.html#MeasureTheory.VectorMeasure.AbsolutelyContinuous.ennrealToMeasure\"><span class=\"name\">MeasureTheory</span>.<span class=\"name\">VectorMeasure</span>.<span class=\"name\">Absolutely